sections.english:
At Sāvatthi. Then a certain wealthy brahmin, unkempt and wearing rough garments, approached the Blessed One. Having approached, he exchanged greetings with the Blessed One. After exchanging courteous and memorable remarks, he sat down to one side. To that wealthy brahmin, seated to one side, the Blessed One said this: "Brahmin, why are you unkempt and wearing rough garments?"

"Here, Venerable Gotama, I have four sons. They, after consulting with their wives, have driven me out of the house."

"In that case, Brahmin, learn these verses and recite them in the assembly when a large crowd has gathered and your sons are also present."

"Those for whose birth I rejoiced, and for whose welfare I wished;
They, after consulting with their wives, drive me away as if from a pig sty.

These wretched ones, though they say 'Father, father' to me;
Are demons in the guise of sons, abandoning me in my old age.

Just as an old, useless horse is removed from the feeding trough;
So the aged father of children now begs in others' houses.

Indeed, a staff would be better for me than these disobedient sons;
For it wards off even a fierce bull, and also a fierce dog.

When it is dark in front, it helps one find solid ground in deep places;
By the power of the staff, one recovers if one stumbling and stands firm again."

Then that wealthy brahmin, having learned these verses from the Blessed One, recited them in the assembly when a large crowd had gathered and his sons were also present:

"Those for whose birth I rejoiced, and for whose welfare I wished;
They, after consulting with their wives, drive me away as if from a pig sty.

These wretched ones, though they say 'Father, father' to me;
Are demons in the guise of sons, abandoning me in my old age.

Just as an old, useless horse is removed from the feeding trough;
So the aged father of children now begs in others' houses.

Indeed, a staff would be better for me than these disobedient sons;
For it wards off even a fierce bull, and also a fierce dog.

When it is dark in front, it helps one find solid ground in deep places;
By the power of the staff, one recovers if one stumbles and stands firm again."

Then his sons took the wealthy brahmin home, bathed him, and individually presented him with a pair of garments. Then that wealthy brahmin, taking one pair of garments, approached the Blessed One. Having approached, he exchanged greetings with the Blessed One. After exchanging courteous and memorable remarks, he sat down to one side. Seated to one side, the wealthy brahmin said this to the Blessed One: "Venerable Gotama, we brahmins are accustomed to seeking a teacher's fee for our teacher. May Venerable Gotama accept this teacher's fee from me." The Blessed One accepted it out of compassion. Then that wealthy brahmin said to the Blessed One: "Excellent, Venerable Gotama! Excellent, Venerable Gotama! Just as if one were to set upright what had been overturned, or to reveal what had been hidden, or to point out the way to one who was lost, or to carry a lamp into the darkness so those with eyes could see forms, even so has Venerable Gotama made the Dhamma clear in many ways. I go for refuge to Venerable Gotama, to the Dhamma, and to the Saṅgha of bhikkhus. May Venerable Gotama accept me as a lay follower who has taken refuge from this day forth as long as life lasts."
